pull_request.title: feat: Include password in user creation and update return values
pull_request.body:
This pull request updates the user creation and update logic in the Postgres repository to ensure the `password` field is included in both the returned columns and the scanned struct after an insert or update operation. This change helps maintain consistency and ensures the full user model, including the password, is available after these operations.

**Repository query and model updates:**

* Added the `password` field to the list of returned columns in both the `Create` and `Update` user queries in `repository.go`, ensuring the password is populated in the resulting `User` model. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-68a3e6ef41ab86f6268ccb6d454351dd74ef6fb06662477dd88cf603ff9e92dbL53-R59) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-68a3e6ef41ab86f6268ccb6d454351dd74ef6fb06662477dd88cf603ff9e92dbL262-R269)
* Updated the `Scan` calls to include the `Password` field, so the `User` struct returned from these methods contains the password value. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-68a3e6ef41ab86f6268ccb6d454351dd74ef6fb06662477dd88cf603ff9e92dbL53-R59) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-68a3e6ef41ab86f6268ccb6d454351dd74ef6fb06662477dd88cf603ff9e92dbL262-R269)

pull_request.title: test: Add concurrent fixture teardown test for Hypothesis
pull_request.body:
This PR improves test coverage for the Hypothesis integration by adding a new test case for concurrent fixture teardowns.

The new `test_hypothesis_concurrent_fixture_teardown` test validates that `async` fixtures with teardown logic behave correctly when run alongside other concurrent tasks. This helps ensure the robustness of `pytest-asyncio`'s fixture management in complex, real-world scenarios.

To accommodate Hypothesis's health checks for function-scoped fixtures, the test is decorated with `@settings(suppress_health_check=[HealthCheck.function_scoped_fixture])`.

pull_request.title: [New Website] Screenreader audit
pull_request.body:
# Changes

- Notion [ticket](https://www.notion.so/Perform-screenreader-audit-24c0ad723ce180839543e14f2cfcb6d1?source=copy_link)

We should make an effort to ensure that the website is as accessible by anyone, regardless of their way of using the website.  This includes individuals who navigate the website using only their keyboard (and by using Screen Reader technology)

I audited the website using only a screen reader to check for things like image alt text, correct button labels, semantic navigation, intuitive labels, etc.

Made a few fixes to make things as clear as possible to someone who might be navigating the website blind for example, or who might not be able to use their mouse.

# Test plan
- Test out website using screen reader technology

issue.title: [WIP] Add Kimi-Audio integration for vLLM
issue.body:
## Purpose
This PR adds a new multi‚Äëmodal audio integration (‚ÄúKimi‚ÄëAudio‚Äù) into vLLM.  
It introduces:
- `KimiAudioConfig` and associated `KimiAudioProcessingInfo` to register the model config.  
- `KimiAudioMultiModalProcessor` and `KimiAudioDummyInputsBuilder` to handle audio + text preprocessing.  
- `MoonshotKimiaForCausalLM` (with `SupportsMultiModal`, `SupportsPP`) that wires in `WhisperEncoder` and `VQAdaptor` behind the scenes.  
Resolves: [Issue #17234].

## Test Plan
1. Clone the branch and install vLLM dependencies.  
2. Run the provided integration test script:
   ```bash
   python tests/test_kimia_integration.py

issue.title: feat: support different node selector and toleration for operator, metric server and webhooks
issue.body:
Signed-off-by: AvivGuiser <avivguiser@gmail.com>

<!-- Thank you for contributing!

     Read more about how you can contribute in our contribution guide:
     https://github.com/kedacore/charts/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md
-->

this PR introduces a new separate values for tolerations and node selector for metric server, operator, webhook.
i do think this is a breaking change, a way to maybe make it not a breaking change is to add the node selector and toleration under each spec (while keeping the global one) instead of doing a key per component under the nodeSelector and toleration spec. 
let me know if you want me to implement it that way.  

### Checklist

- [X] I have verified that my change is according to the [deprecations & breaking changes policy](https://github.com/kedacore/governance/blob/main/DEPRECATIONS.md)
- [X] Commits are signed with Developer Certificate of Origin (DCO - [learn more](https://github.com/kedacore/charts/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#developer-certificate-of-origin-signing-your-work))
- [x] README is updated with new configuration values *(if applicable)* [learn more](https://github.com/kedacore/charts/blob/main/CONTRIBUTING.md#documentation)
- [x] A PR is opened to update KEDA core ([repo](https://github.com/kedacore/keda)) *(if applicable, ie. when deployment manifests are modified)*

comment.body:
> Hello We must avoid breaking changes. Please do it in a way that avoids breaking change, for example, defining this new fields under operator.tolerations, metrics-server.tolerations, etc and use the current value as default if the other isn't defined

Hi, i updated the PR accordingly
